The start symbol S can only expand to two non-terminals (NT49 NT35, NT36 NT32, NT20 NT53).  
There are no ε-productions anywhere in the grammar, so each of those two non-terminals must eventually yield at least one terminal symbol. Therefore every sentence generated from S contains at least two terminals.  

The target string “t3” is only one terminal long, so it cannot be produced by any derivation from S.  

No

In the grammar every derivation of the start symbol S must begin with one of the following productions  

1. S → NT49 NT35  
2. S → NT36 NT32  
3. S → NT20 NT53  

 • If production (1) is used, the very last word of the sentence must be the single terminal generated by NT35, namely t9.  
 • If production (3) is used, the last word must be the single terminal generated by NT53, namely t8.  
The given sentence ends with t5, so productions (1) and (3) are impossible.  
Therefore only production (2) can be used and the string must be split into  

 (sentence generated by NT36) · (sentence generated by NT32)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
The right-hand child NT32 is forced to expand by the only rule it has:

 NT32 → NT50 NT55

Thus the tail of the whole sentence is the concatenation of a block produced by NT50 followed by a block produced by NT55, i.e.

 … · (tokens from NT50) · (tokens from NT55)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Look at the last two words of the sentence, “… t6 t5”.

1. NT55 can be
   a) a single token t4 / t0 / t7, or  
   b) NT50 NT49, whose last token is always the terminal of NT49 (t8), or  
   c) NT57 NT29, whose first token is always t5 (from NT57).  
   In every case the *last* token produced by NT55 is one of
   t4, t0, t7, t8 or (from NT29) t5 / t6 / t9.

   Hence the only way NT55 could end in “… t6 t5” is via option (c) with
   NT57 ⇒ t5 and NT29 ⇒ t6, i.e. the last two tokens would have to be “t5 t6”.

2. But our sentence ends with “t6 t5”, the reverse order.  
   So no expansion of NT55 can produce the tail “… t6 t5”.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Because NT55 cannot end with “… t6 t5”, the final “… t6 t5” would have to belong to NT50.  
That would leave NT55 with **no words at all**, which is impossible—every production in this Chomsky-normal-form grammar produces at least one terminal.

Hence no derivation exists in which S ⇒ NT36 NT32 yields the given 46-word sentence, and the other two top-level productions are already impossible.

Therefore the string is **not** generated by the grammar.

No

To come from the start symbol S the string has to be produced by one of the three rules

1. S → NT49 NT35  (last symbol would be the single terminal produced by NT35 = t9)
2. S → NT20 NT53  (last symbol would be the single terminal produced by NT53 = t8)
3. S → NT36 NT32  (last symbol must come from NT32)

The given string ends with t7, so only rule 3 can possibly apply.

––––  What can NT36 start with?  
NT36 has only the following possibilities:

• NT36 → 't1'           (first symbol t1)  
• NT36 → NT15 NT38      (first symbol t4, because NT15 → 't4')  
• NT36 → NT56 NT43

Thus the only way to avoid starting with t1 or t4 is to use the last alternative.  
So the first symbol of the whole string would be the first symbol produced by NT56.

––––  What can NT56 start with?  
NT56 → NT32 NT12, so its first symbol is the first from NT32.

––––  What can NT32 start with?  
NT32 → NT50 NT55, so its first symbol is the first from NT50.

––––  What can NT50 start with?  
NT50 has

• NT50 → 't5'   (first symbol t5)  
• NT50 → 't3'   (first symbol t3)  
• NT50 → NT0 NT48

To avoid starting with t5 or t3 we must take the third alternative, whose first symbol is the first from NT0.

––––  What can NT0 start with?  
NT0 → 't6'               (first symbol t6)  
NT0 → NT56 NT32   (first symbol from NT56)

Choosing the terminal alternative would give t6; choosing the second puts us back exactly where we were (NT56 again).  
Therefore the only terminals that can ever appear as the very first symbol along this left-most chain are

 t3  (from NT50 → 't3')  
 t5  (from NT50 → 't5')  
 t6  (from NT0  → 't6')

The terminal t0 can never be reached as the first symbol when S → NT36 NT32 is used.

Since rules 1 and 2 force the string to end with t9 or t8 (respectively) and rule 3 cannot produce a string whose first symbol is t0, the grammar is incapable of generating a string that starts with t0 and ends with t7.

The given string begins with t0 and ends with t7, so it is not in the language of the grammar.
